1
00:00:37,450 --> 00:00:41,911
On September 3rd 1973
at 6:28pm and 32 seconds,

2
00:00:41,954 --> 00:00:47,197
a bluebottle fly capable
of 14,670 wing beats a minute

3
00:00:47,251 --> 00:00:49,624
landed on Rue St Vincent, Montmartre.

4
00:00:54,092 --> 00:00:58,386
At the same moment,
on a restaurant terrace nearby,

5
00:00:58,429 --> 00:01:03,305
the wind magically made two glasses
dance unseen on a tablecloth.

6
00:01:04,477 --> 00:01:10,182
Meanwhile, in a 5th-floor flat,
28 Avenue Trudaine, Paris 9,

7
00:01:10,232 --> 00:01:15,025
returning from his best friend's funeral,
Eugène Colère erased his name

8
00:01:15,071 --> 00:01:17,147
from his address book.

9
00:01:21,619 --> 00:01:25,617
At the same moment,
a sperm with one X chromosome,

10
00:01:25,665 --> 00:01:28,072
belonging to Raphaël Poulain,

11
00:01:28,125 --> 00:01:32,170
made a dash for an egg in his wife Amandine.

12
00:01:32,213 --> 00:01:34,290
Nine months later,

13
00:01:34,341 --> 00:01:36,879
Amélie Poulain was born.

14
00:01:41,806 --> 00:01:45,756
[The Fabulous Life Of Amélie Poulain]

15
00:03:21,739 --> 00:03:24,312
Her father, an ex-army doctor,

16
00:03:24,367 --> 00:03:26,823
works at a spa in Enghien-Les-Bains.

17
00:03:26,870 --> 00:03:28,827
[TIGHT LIPS = HARD HEART]

18
00:03:28,872 --> 00:03:30,829
Raphaël Poulain dislikes:

19
00:03:31,875 --> 00:03:35,872
Peeing next to someone else. He also dislikes:

20
00:03:35,920 --> 00:03:38,625
Catching scornful glances at his sandals.

21
00:03:42,218 --> 00:03:45,254
Clingy wet swimming trunks.

22
00:03:47,890 --> 00:03:49,967
Raphaël Poulain likes:

23
00:03:50,018 --> 00:03:52,260
Peeling off large strips of wallpaper.

24
00:03:55,273 --> 00:03:57,847
Lining up all his shoes and polishing them.

25
00:03:58,902 --> 00:04:01,108
Emptying his tool box,

26
00:04:01,154 --> 00:04:04,024
cleaning it out,

27
00:04:04,073 --> 00:04:07,110
and putting everything back.

28
00:04:07,160 --> 00:04:11,289
Amélie's mother, Amandine,
a schoolmistress from Gueugnon,

29
00:04:11,331 --> 00:04:13,407
has always had shaky nerves.

30
00:04:13,458 --> 00:04:15,534
[FACIAL TWITCH = WEAK NERVES]

31
00:04:15,585 --> 00:04:19,879
Amandine Poulain dislikes:
Getting puckered fingers in the bath.

32
00:04:19,923 --> 00:04:22,959
When someone she doesn't like

33
00:04:23,009 --> 00:04:24,717
brushes against her hand.

34
00:04:26,262 --> 00:04:29,631
Pillow marks on her cheek in the morning.

35
00:04:29,682 --> 00:04:34,179
Amandine Poulain likes:
Figure skaters' costumes on TV.

36
00:04:34,229 --> 00:04:37,432
Polishing the parquet with slippers.

37
00:04:37,482 --> 00:04:39,142
Emptying her handbag,

38
00:04:39,192 --> 00:04:40,984
cleaning it out,

39
00:04:41,027 --> 00:04:43,435
and putting everything back.

40
00:04:47,992 --> 00:04:49,819
Amélie is six.

41
00:04:49,869 --> 00:04:53,285
Like all little girls,
she'd like to be hugged by her daddy.

42
00:04:54,332 --> 00:04:58,377
But he never touches her,
except for a monthly checkup.

43
00:04:58,420 --> 00:05:01,125
The thrill of this rare contact

44
00:05:01,173 --> 00:05:03,461
makes her heart beat like a drum.

45
00:05:03,508 --> 00:05:05,050
As a result,

46
00:05:05,093 --> 00:05:07,169
he thinks she has a heart defect.

47
00:05:08,430 --> 00:05:10,718
Declared unfit for school,

48
00:05:10,765 --> 00:05:13,885
Amélie is taught by her mother.

49
00:05:13,935 --> 00:05:15,215
Four...

50
00:05:15,269 --> 00:05:16,384
hens...

51
00:05:16,437 --> 00:05:17,468
brood...

52
00:05:17,522 --> 00:05:19,017
here...

53
00:05:19,066 --> 00:05:21,307
henceforth.

54
00:05:21,360 --> 00:05:23,482
Four hens brood...

55
00:05:23,528 --> 00:05:25,106
Very good.

56
00:05:25,155 --> 00:05:27,728
...hens fourth!
- No!

57
00:05:27,782 --> 00:05:30,452
Deprived of playmates,

58
00:05:30,493 --> 00:05:33,115
tossed about
between a neurotic and an iceberg,

59
00:05:33,163 --> 00:05:36,329
Amélie retreats into her imagination.

60
00:05:37,709 --> 00:05:41,659
In this world, LPs are made like pancakes.

61
00:05:41,713 --> 00:05:44,548
The neighbour's comatose wife

62
00:05:44,591 --> 00:05:48,174
has chosen to get all her life's sleep in one go.

63
00:05:48,220 --> 00:05:51,553
After this, I can stay awake day and night.

64
00:05:54,934 --> 00:05:57,686
Amélie has one friend, Blubber.

65
00:05:57,729 --> 00:06:02,474
Alas, the home environment
has made Blubber suicidal.

66
00:06:20,460 --> 00:06:24,588
Blubber's suicide attempts
destroy Mother's nerves.

67
00:06:24,630 --> 00:06:26,256
A decision is made.

68
00:06:26,300 --> 00:06:27,675
Enough!

69
00:07:01,584 --> 00:07:06,377
To comfort Amélie, her mother
gives her a second-hand Instamatic camera.

70
00:07:18,101 --> 00:07:20,639
Little girl! Look what you did!

71
00:07:20,687 --> 00:07:25,847
A neighbour fools her into thinking
her camera causes accidents.

72
00:07:25,900 --> 00:07:30,562
Because she'd been taking pictures
all afternoon, Amélie is petrified.

73
00:07:31,614 --> 00:07:34,616
She stares at the TV, racked by the guilt

74
00:07:34,660 --> 00:07:36,783
of causing a huge fire,

75
00:07:36,829 --> 00:07:38,738
two derailments

76
00:07:38,789 --> 00:07:40,662
and a jumbo jet crash.

77
00:07:40,707 --> 00:07:42,616
A few days later,

78
00:07:42,667 --> 00:07:44,494
realising she'd been had,

79
00:07:44,544 --> 00:07:46,620
Amélie gets her revenge.

80
00:07:58,058 --> 00:08:00,347
What...?

81
00:08:28,213 --> 00:08:30,289
One day tragedy strikes.

82
00:08:30,340 --> 00:08:35,678
Amandine takes Amélie to Notre Dame
to light a candle and pray for a baby brother.

83
00:08:35,720 --> 00:08:38,092
Three minutes later, heaven sends,

84
00:08:38,139 --> 00:08:43,300
alas, not a baby boy, but Marguerite,
a tourist from Quebec,

85
00:08:43,353 --> 00:08:45,429
bent on ending her life.

86
00:08:48,066 --> 00:08:49,975
Amandine Poulain is killed instantly.

87
00:08:53,405 --> 00:08:58,280
After her mother's death,
Amélie lives alone with her father.

88
00:08:58,326 --> 00:09:02,371
His unsociable tendencies increase.

89
00:09:02,413 --> 00:09:05,866
He's obsessed with building a miniature shrine

90
00:09:05,918 --> 00:09:08,124
to house his wife's ashes.

91
00:09:14,134 --> 00:09:16,755
Days, months and years go by.

92
00:09:21,641 --> 00:09:23,717
In such a dead world,

93
00:09:23,768 --> 00:09:27,434
Amélie prefers to dream
until she's old enough to leave home.

94
00:09:37,783 --> 00:09:41,116
Five years later,
she's a waitress in Montmartre

95
00:09:41,161 --> 00:09:43,319
at The Two Windmills.

96
00:09:44,622 --> 00:09:46,282
It is August 29th.

97
00:09:46,332 --> 00:09:50,034
In 48 hours, her life will change for ever.

98
00:09:51,922 --> 00:09:54,709
But she doesn't know it yet.

99
00:09:54,758 --> 00:09:59,420
She lives quietly among her colleagues
and the café's regulars.

100
00:09:59,471 --> 00:10:01,962
That's Suzanne, the owner.

101
00:10:02,015 --> 00:10:04,850
She limps a little but she's never spilt a drink.

102
00:10:04,893 --> 00:10:08,012
When she was younger, she was a circus rider.

103
00:10:08,062 --> 00:10:10,637
She likes athletes who cry with disappointment.

104
00:10:10,691 --> 00:10:15,685
She dislikes seeing men humiliated
in front of their kids in her café.

105
00:10:15,738 --> 00:10:19,687
Georgette is the tobacconist.
She's a hypochondriac.

106
00:10:19,741 --> 00:10:24,450
Migraines one day, sciatica the next.
She hates the words

107
00:10:24,496 --> 00:10:26,702
"fruit of thy womb".

108
00:10:26,748 --> 00:10:30,911
Gina works with Amélie.
Her grandmother was a healer.

109
00:10:30,960 --> 00:10:33,962
She likes cracking bones.

110
00:10:34,006 --> 00:10:37,422
She's bringing a kir to Hipolito, a failed writer.

111
00:10:37,468 --> 00:10:41,002
He likes seeing bullfighters gored on TV.

112
00:10:43,015 --> 00:10:47,557
Scowling at them is Joseph,
Gina's rejected lover.

113
00:10:47,602 --> 00:10:50,176
He's always jealously spying on her.

114
00:10:50,230 --> 00:10:51,973
All he likes

115
00:10:52,023 --> 00:10:54,978
is popping bubble wrap.

116
00:10:55,027 --> 00:10:57,483
And here's Philomène, an air hostess.

117
00:10:57,530 --> 00:11:01,527
Amélie looks after her cat Rodrigue
when she's away. Philomène likes

118
00:11:01,575 --> 00:11:04,492
the sound of the cat's bowl on the tiles.

119
00:11:04,536 --> 00:11:08,486
Rodrigue likes overhearing children's stories.

120
00:11:09,791 --> 00:11:12,329
No, thanks, ma'am. I never work on Sundays.

121
00:11:13,378 --> 00:11:18,088
At weekends, Amélie often takes a train
from the Gare du Nord to see her father.

122
00:11:18,134 --> 00:11:22,083
- Why don't you use your retirement to...?
- To do what?

123
00:11:22,137 --> 00:11:24,213
Travel. You've never been away.

124
00:11:25,891 --> 00:11:29,805
When we were young,
your mother and I longed to travel.

125
00:11:31,271 --> 00:11:33,347
But we couldn't.

126
00:11:33,398 --> 00:11:36,399
- Because of your heart.
- Yes. I know.

127
00:11:36,443 --> 00:11:38,815
So now...

128
00:11:38,862 --> 00:11:40,689
Now...

129
00:11:40,740 --> 00:11:43,575
Some Friday evenings,
Amélie goes to the cinema.

130
00:11:43,617 --> 00:11:47,282
I like turning round
and looking at people's faces in the dark.

131
00:11:53,794 --> 00:11:57,661
I like noticing details
that no-one else ever sees.

132
00:12:00,216 --> 00:12:04,297
But I hate it in old American movies
when drivers don't watch the road.

133
00:12:09,768 --> 00:12:12,140
Amélie doesn't have a boyfriend.

134
00:12:12,187 --> 00:12:16,564
She tried once or twice,
but the results were a let-down.

135
00:12:16,608 --> 00:12:20,440
Instead, she cultivates a taste
for small pleasures.

136
00:12:21,488 --> 00:12:23,979
Plunging her hand deep into a sack of grain.

137
00:12:24,032 --> 00:12:26,785
Cracking crème brûlée

138
00:12:26,827 --> 00:12:28,867
with a teaspoon.

139
00:12:32,791 --> 00:12:35,461
And skimming stones on the Canal St Martin.

140
00:13:16,418 --> 00:13:19,336
They call him the Glass Man.

141
00:13:19,380 --> 00:13:22,131
He was born with bones as brittle as crystal.

142
00:13:23,175 --> 00:13:25,630
All his furniture is padded.

143
00:13:25,677 --> 00:13:29,011
A handshake would be enough
to crush his fingers.

144
00:13:29,055 --> 00:13:31,214
He's stayed indoors for 20 years.

145
00:13:35,354 --> 00:13:37,430
Time has changed nothing.

146
00:13:37,481 --> 00:13:39,806
Amélie still takes refuge in solitude.

147
00:13:39,858 --> 00:13:44,520
She amuses herself with silly questions
about the world below,

148
00:13:44,571 --> 00:13:48,569
such as: "How many couples
are having an orgasm now?"

149
00:13:58,836 --> 00:13:59,999
Fifteen.

150
00:14:03,215 --> 00:14:05,967
Finally, on the night of August 30th 1997.

151
00:14:06,009 --> 00:14:10,671
comes the event
that will change her life for ever.

152
00:14:10,722 --> 00:14:15,349
Lady Di, Princess of Wales,
died in a car crash in Paris last night

153
00:14:15,393 --> 00:14:19,309
with her companion Dodi Al Fayed...

154
00:15:10,157 --> 00:15:13,858
Only the first man
to discover Tutankhamen's tomb

155
00:15:13,911 --> 00:15:15,987
would understand how she felt

156
00:15:16,038 --> 00:15:18,280
on finding this treasure

157
00:15:18,332 --> 00:15:22,163
hidden by a little boy 40 years ago.

158
00:15:27,675 --> 00:15:30,248
On August 31st at 4am,

159
00:15:30,302 --> 00:15:33,339
Amélie has a dazzling idea.

160
00:15:33,389 --> 00:15:36,923
Wherever he was,
she would find the box's owner

161
00:15:36,975 --> 00:15:39,301
and give him back his treasure.

162
00:15:39,353 --> 00:15:44,098
If he was touched,
she'd become a regular do-gooder.

163
00:15:44,149 --> 00:15:46,142
If not, too bad.

164
00:15:53,075 --> 00:15:56,907
The girl from the 5th floor!
We don't see much of you.

165
00:15:56,954 --> 00:16:01,248
Would you know of a boy
who lived in my flat in the '50s?

166
00:16:01,291 --> 00:16:03,533
A boy? Come and have a glass of port.

167
00:16:05,295 --> 00:16:08,130
- No, thanks.
- Come in! Close the door.

168
00:16:08,173 --> 00:16:12,302
Boys? I've known so many.

169
00:16:12,345 --> 00:16:16,638
They're cute until they discover
snowballs and chestnuts.

170
00:16:16,682 --> 00:16:18,758
I've known so many boys.

171
00:16:18,809 --> 00:16:22,344
- When did you come here?
- In '64.

172
00:16:22,396 --> 00:16:25,148
You'll have heard the story.

173
00:16:25,190 --> 00:16:27,397
No, I don't think so.

174
00:16:27,442 --> 00:16:29,269
I'm amazed. Sit down.

175
00:16:30,987 --> 00:16:33,989
My husband worked for Ladybird Insurance.

176
00:16:34,033 --> 00:16:37,484
It's no secret that he slept with his secretary.

177
00:16:39,038 --> 00:16:41,493
They used every hotel around.

178
00:16:41,540 --> 00:16:43,248
Not the grotty ones, either.

179
00:16:43,292 --> 00:16:46,625
The bimbo liked spreading her legs,

180
00:16:46,670 --> 00:16:48,164
but only on satin.

181
00:16:48,213 --> 00:16:51,214
So my husband swiped from the till.

182
00:16:51,258 --> 00:16:54,295
A little at first, then 50 million.

183
00:16:54,345 --> 00:16:57,631
Off they flew to South America.

184
00:16:59,892 --> 00:17:00,923
Drink up.

185
00:17:02,978 --> 00:17:06,015
On January 20th 1970,

186
00:17:06,065 --> 00:17:08,472
my doorbell rang.

187
00:17:08,525 --> 00:17:13,602
"Your husband's been killed
in a car crash in South America."

188
00:17:14,698 --> 00:17:16,775
My life stopped there.

189
00:17:16,826 --> 00:17:19,993
And Black Lion died of heartbreak.

190
00:17:20,037 --> 00:17:22,872
Poor creature.

191
00:17:25,418 --> 00:17:27,493
See how lovingly

192
00:17:27,545 --> 00:17:29,584
he still stares at his master?

193
00:17:30,631 --> 00:17:31,662
One day

194
00:17:31,715 --> 00:17:33,209
I'll read you his letters.

195
00:17:33,258 --> 00:17:35,002
No, don't go!

196
00:17:35,052 --> 00:17:37,507
You can spare five minutes.

197
00:17:37,554 --> 00:17:39,215
He wrote this

198
00:17:39,265 --> 00:17:40,925
from the barracks.

199
00:17:43,519 --> 00:17:45,013
"Darling Mado." That's me.

200
00:17:45,062 --> 00:17:46,722
I'm called Madeleine.

201
00:17:46,772 --> 00:17:49,773
"I can't sleep, can't eat,

202
00:17:49,817 --> 00:17:54,609
knowing that my only reason to live
is far away in Paris.

203
00:17:54,655 --> 00:17:57,062
I won't see her until a fortnight on Friday,

204
00:17:57,116 --> 00:18:02,905
when my sweet little weasel
appears at the station

205
00:18:02,955 --> 00:18:06,040
in her strappy blue dress."

206
00:18:06,083 --> 00:18:10,128
In brackets: "The one you think
is too transparent."

207
00:18:18,679 --> 00:18:21,004
Has anyone ever written to you like that?

208
00:18:21,056 --> 00:18:25,137
No. I'm nobody's little weasel.

209
00:18:25,186 --> 00:18:27,759
My name's Madeleine Wells.

210
00:18:27,814 --> 00:18:30,898
Madeleine, like Mary Magdalene.

211
00:18:30,942 --> 00:18:34,441
She wept, right? And Wells as in water.

212
00:18:34,487 --> 00:18:38,698
Talk about being born to cry!

213
00:18:42,286 --> 00:18:44,112
About your question...

214
00:18:44,163 --> 00:18:49,620
Ask Collignon, the grocer.
He's lived here all his life.

215
00:18:50,670 --> 00:18:53,077
Hello, Amélie-mellow!

216
00:18:53,130 --> 00:18:55,668
A fig and three hazelnuts, as usual?

217
00:18:55,716 --> 00:18:58,503
Who lived in my flat in the '50s?

218
00:18:58,552 --> 00:19:02,550
- What was their name?
- You've got me there, dear.

219
00:19:02,598 --> 00:19:06,547
In 1950, I was two.
The mental age of this cretin.

220
00:19:06,602 --> 00:19:08,226
The "cretin" is Lucien.

221
00:19:08,270 --> 00:19:12,315
He's no genius, but Amélie likes him.
She likes the way

222
00:19:12,358 --> 00:19:15,692
he handles each endive like a precious object

223
00:19:15,736 --> 00:19:18,939
to be treated with care.
It's his way of showing

224
00:19:18,990 --> 00:19:20,400
his love of good work.

225
00:19:20,449 --> 00:19:21,480
Look at him!

226
00:19:21,534 --> 00:19:25,994
Like he's nursing a baby bird
that's fallen out of its nest!

227
00:19:26,038 --> 00:19:28,707
Don't ask him for currants!

228
00:19:28,749 --> 00:19:30,373
You'd be here till Monday!

229
00:19:31,669 --> 00:19:33,578
Get moving, spastic!

230
00:19:33,630 --> 00:19:35,669
She hasn't got all day.

231
00:19:38,509 --> 00:19:40,715
Here.

232
00:19:40,761 --> 00:19:44,462
Go and see my mother.
She has the memory of an elephant.

233
00:19:44,515 --> 00:19:46,673
Elephant Mum!

234
00:19:47,977 --> 00:19:49,471
Thank you.

235
00:20:07,955 --> 00:20:09,200
Bredoteau.

236
00:20:10,791 --> 00:20:11,822
Sorry?

237
00:20:11,875 --> 00:20:13,667
It's the name you're after.

238
00:20:13,711 --> 00:20:18,124
But if it's me that says so,
it won't count. I'm senile.

239
00:20:18,174 --> 00:20:20,131
Ignore him. He's senile.

240
00:20:21,177 --> 00:20:23,253
See what he's done to my laurel?

241
00:20:27,391 --> 00:20:30,061
His old job was punching métro tickets.

242
00:20:30,102 --> 00:20:35,309
For three months now,
he's got up every night to punch holes

243
00:20:35,357 --> 00:20:38,857
- in my laurels!
- I'd have preferred lilacs. Such is life!

244
00:20:38,903 --> 00:20:43,364
- We all need a way to relax.
- I skim stones.

245
00:20:43,408 --> 00:20:47,571
- You do?
- I'll find it. Don't worry.

246
00:20:47,620 --> 00:20:50,574
- I file everything.
- Like what?

247
00:20:50,623 --> 00:20:55,415
Your son's nearly 50
and I'm still doing his book-keeping.

248
00:20:55,461 --> 00:21:00,169
You were still squeezing his toothpaste at 15,
so it follows.

249
00:21:00,215 --> 00:21:02,588
Right. Camus...

250
00:21:02,635 --> 00:21:06,633
2nd floor on the right. Brossard...
Brossard was on staircase B.

251
00:21:06,681 --> 00:21:08,258
Got it!

252
00:21:08,307 --> 00:21:10,430
Bredoteau, 5th floor on the right.

253
00:21:10,476 --> 00:21:13,228
They were from the Pas de Calais.

254
00:21:13,271 --> 00:21:15,892
Bredoteau. What more can I say?

255
00:22:20,755 --> 00:22:24,337
Groping under the photo booth
is Nino Quincampoix.

256
00:22:28,804 --> 00:22:33,467
When Amélie lacked playmates,
Nino had too many.

257
00:22:44,612 --> 00:22:49,689
Five miles apart, one dreamed
of having a sister, the other a brother

258
00:22:49,742 --> 00:22:51,781
to spend all their time with.

259
00:23:13,432 --> 00:23:14,463
Hi, Dad.

260
00:23:16,102 --> 00:23:17,478
A new friend?

261
00:23:18,521 --> 00:23:20,728
No, I've had him for years.

262
00:23:20,773 --> 00:23:24,688
Your mother hated him,
so he lived in the tool shed.

263
00:23:24,736 --> 00:23:27,736
There. Let's reconcile them.

264
00:23:31,158 --> 00:23:33,234
There. Not bad, eh?

265
00:23:37,122 --> 00:23:42,580
Dad, if you found a precious relic
from your childhood,

266
00:23:42,629 --> 00:23:46,496
how would it make you feel?
Happy? Sad? Nostalgic? What?

267
00:23:47,592 --> 00:23:50,083
I didn't have this gnome when I was a child.

268
00:23:50,136 --> 00:23:53,754
He was a retirement gift from my old regiment.

269
00:23:53,806 --> 00:23:58,267
No, I mean something you hid
like a secret treasure.

270
00:23:59,812 --> 00:24:01,889
I should varnish him before autumn.

271
00:24:05,819 --> 00:24:08,440
I'll make some tea. Do you want some?

272
00:24:08,488 --> 00:24:10,564
Breathe in. Hold still.

273
00:24:12,658 --> 00:24:14,366
Better now?

274
00:24:14,410 --> 00:24:16,284
Shut the door!

275
00:24:16,329 --> 00:24:18,368
There's a howling gale.

276
00:24:18,414 --> 00:24:20,406
It's hardly Siberia.

277
00:24:20,458 --> 00:24:23,032
I can see you're not allergic

278
00:24:23,086 --> 00:24:27,748
to car fumes.
I almost coughed up my pleura last night.

279
00:24:27,799 --> 00:24:29,293
Coughed up a pleura? Sure.

280
00:24:29,342 --> 00:24:32,925
- What's on the menu today, Suzanne?
- Endives au gratin.

281
00:24:32,971 --> 00:24:35,426
They'll have you on your knees, you'll see.

282
00:24:35,473 --> 00:24:36,671
They're good, then?

283
00:24:36,724 --> 00:24:38,930
- Depends where.
- If it's at the toilet...

284
00:24:38,976 --> 00:24:40,257
Not good!

285
00:24:45,817 --> 00:24:49,767
12:15, laughs orgasmically
to attract alpha male.

286
00:24:49,821 --> 00:24:52,738
He's going to drive me berserk!

287
00:24:52,782 --> 00:24:56,531
Can't he give up?
There are plenty of other bars.

288
00:24:56,577 --> 00:24:58,535
Goodbye.

289
00:24:58,579 --> 00:24:59,824
Suzanne.

290
00:24:59,872 --> 00:25:01,781
- Suzanne.
- Yes.

291
00:25:01,832 --> 00:25:04,584
"Au gratin" means white sauce, right?

292
00:25:04,627 --> 00:25:06,251
Yes, why?

293
00:25:06,295 --> 00:25:11,337
I can't stomach it. Like you and horse meat.

294
00:25:11,384 --> 00:25:14,136
It's not my stomach, it's my memory.

295
00:25:15,180 --> 00:25:16,971
I'd rather cook human flesh.

296
00:25:17,015 --> 00:25:19,054
You're kidding!

297
00:25:30,194 --> 00:25:34,572
Suzanne, would you mind if I left early today?

298
00:25:34,616 --> 00:25:36,655
What's his name?

299
00:25:36,701 --> 00:25:38,777
Dominique Bredoteau.

300
00:25:44,333 --> 00:25:46,160
Hello.

301
00:25:47,295 --> 00:25:49,204
Are you Dominique Bredoteau?

302
00:25:49,255 --> 00:25:50,630
That's me.

303
00:25:50,673 --> 00:25:52,665
Why?

304
00:25:52,716 --> 00:25:54,793
It's about...

305
00:25:55,846 --> 00:25:57,090
...the petition.

306
00:25:57,138 --> 00:25:58,549
Petition?

307
00:25:58,598 --> 00:26:03,343
Yes. The petition to...

308
00:26:04,771 --> 00:26:06,680
...to canonise Lady Di.

309
00:26:06,731 --> 00:26:08,391
No, thanks.

310
00:26:08,441 --> 00:26:09,472
No.

311
00:26:17,284 --> 00:26:19,857
Ladies and gentlemen, sorry to bother you...

312
00:26:24,833 --> 00:26:26,991
- Yes?
- Hello.

313
00:26:27,043 --> 00:26:30,708
I'm looking for Dominique Bredoteau
for the European census.

314
00:26:31,881 --> 00:26:33,920
Come up. Third floor.

315
00:26:44,269 --> 00:26:45,300
Hello, kitten.

316
00:26:48,690 --> 00:26:49,888
Earl Grey?

317
00:26:49,941 --> 00:26:52,017
Jasmine?

318
00:26:52,068 --> 00:26:55,104
What will you have?

319
00:26:58,991 --> 00:27:00,451
I'm working.

320
00:27:09,252 --> 00:27:12,123
There. I'm coming.

321
00:27:12,172 --> 00:27:16,549
Do you know where I can find
Dominique Bredoteau?

322
00:27:16,592 --> 00:27:18,881
Oh, my poor dear!

323
00:27:19,971 --> 00:27:21,133
You just missed him.

324
00:27:22,181 --> 00:27:24,934
Look, there he goes now.

325
00:27:34,402 --> 00:27:35,433
Bre-to-deau.

326
00:27:36,946 --> 00:27:38,357
Not Bre-do-teau.

327
00:27:38,406 --> 00:27:40,280
You need

328
00:27:40,324 --> 00:27:43,824
a glass of mulled wine.

329
00:27:43,869 --> 00:27:45,697
Come in.

330
00:27:45,747 --> 00:27:46,992
Come on in.

331
00:27:50,001 --> 00:27:54,628
I've lived here for five years.
This is the first time we've met.

332
00:27:54,673 --> 00:27:57,460
I never go out on the landing.

333
00:27:57,509 --> 00:28:01,506
I'm fussy about who I meet.

334
00:28:01,554 --> 00:28:03,132
They're all creeps anyway.

335
00:28:05,349 --> 00:28:07,924
Come in. Here.

336
00:28:07,978 --> 00:28:09,353
Come in.

337
00:28:10,397 --> 00:28:12,970
They call me the Glass Man,

338
00:28:13,024 --> 00:28:16,607
but my name is Raymond Dufayel.

339
00:28:17,737 --> 00:28:22,031
- Amélie Poulain. I'm a waitress at...
- The Two Windmills. I know.

340
00:28:23,076 --> 00:28:28,200
And you've come back empty-handed
from your search for Bretodeau.

341
00:28:29,707 --> 00:28:32,958
Because it's not "do", it's "to".

342
00:28:33,003 --> 00:28:35,541
- Like "Toto".
- Thank you.

343
00:28:39,342 --> 00:28:41,050
I love that painting.

344
00:28:41,094 --> 00:28:43,799
It's the Luncheon Of The Boating Party.

345
00:28:45,515 --> 00:28:46,546
By Renoir.

346
00:28:52,397 --> 00:28:56,347
I've painted one each year for twenty years.

347
00:28:57,986 --> 00:29:00,691
The hardest part is the looks.

348
00:29:00,739 --> 00:29:06,824
I sometimes feel they deliberately change
their mood as soon as my back's turned.

349
00:29:06,870 --> 00:29:08,529
They look quite happy there.

350
00:29:08,580 --> 00:29:10,868
They should be.

351
00:29:10,915 --> 00:29:12,991
This year they had hare with morels.

352
00:29:14,210 --> 00:29:17,829
And waffles with jam for the children.

353
00:29:17,881 --> 00:29:23,385
Now, what have I done
with that piece of paper?

354
00:29:25,513 --> 00:29:30,887
Ah, you've noticed my video camera
at the window.

355
00:29:30,935 --> 00:29:33,604
It's a gift from my sister-in-law.

356
00:29:33,646 --> 00:29:36,517
I put it there

357
00:29:36,566 --> 00:29:39,484
so I don't need to wind up my clocks.

358
00:29:40,904 --> 00:29:43,525
After all these years,

359
00:29:43,573 --> 00:29:47,902
the only person I still can't capture

360
00:29:47,953 --> 00:29:50,241
is the girl with the glass of water.

361
00:29:50,288 --> 00:29:51,782
She's in the middle,

362
00:29:51,831 --> 00:29:54,666
yet she's on the outside.

363
00:29:56,294 --> 00:29:58,867
Maybe she's just different from the others.

364
00:30:00,257 --> 00:30:01,716
In what way?

365
00:30:03,385 --> 00:30:04,796
I don't know.

366
00:30:04,845 --> 00:30:10,087
When she was little, she can't
have played much with other children.

367
00:30:11,893 --> 00:30:14,182
Maybe never.

368
00:30:17,899 --> 00:30:19,274
Here.

369
00:30:19,317 --> 00:30:23,267
Dominique Bretodeau, 27 Rue Mouffetard.

370
00:30:24,573 --> 00:30:25,853
It's for you.

371
00:30:27,075 --> 00:30:32,070
Every Tuesday morning,
Dominique Bretodeau goes to buy a chicken.

372
00:30:32,122 --> 00:30:35,241
He usually roasts it
and has it with sauté potatoes.

373
00:30:35,291 --> 00:30:38,577
After carving the legs,
the breast and the wings,

374
00:30:38,628 --> 00:30:42,672
he loves picking the hot carcass
with his fingers,

375
00:30:42,715 --> 00:30:44,375
starting with the oysters.

376
00:30:47,554 --> 00:30:51,386
But not today. Bretodeau won't buy a chicken.

377
00:30:51,433 --> 00:30:52,892
He'll go no further

378
00:30:52,934 --> 00:30:54,594
than this phone booth here.

379
00:32:04,965 --> 00:32:08,298
In a flash, it all came back to him.

380
00:32:08,343 --> 00:32:11,546
Federico Bahamontes
winning the Tour de France in '59.

381
00:32:14,558 --> 00:32:16,634
Aunt Josette's slips.

382
00:32:19,188 --> 00:32:22,272
And most of all, that tragic day.

383
00:32:23,650 --> 00:32:27,268
That tragic day
when he won all the marbles at break time.

384
00:32:36,120 --> 00:32:37,153
Bretodeau!

385
00:32:40,334 --> 00:32:41,496
Bretodeau!

386
00:32:48,884 --> 00:32:51,256
The pinch, Bretodeau!

387
00:32:51,303 --> 00:32:53,379
Do you understand, Bretodeau?

388
00:33:01,105 --> 00:33:02,480
Cognac, please.

389
00:33:07,861 --> 00:33:10,566
It's amazing, what just happened to me.

390
00:33:10,614 --> 00:33:14,825
It must be my guardian angel.
It's the only explanation.

391
00:33:14,868 --> 00:33:17,323
It was as if the phone booth was calling me.

392
00:33:17,370 --> 00:33:19,778
It rang and rang.

393
00:33:22,293 --> 00:33:25,377
Same here. The microwave's calling me.

394
00:33:27,631 --> 00:33:29,707
I'll have another cognac.

395
00:33:38,391 --> 00:33:39,850
Life's strange.

396
00:33:42,353 --> 00:33:46,767
To a kid, time always drags.
Suddenly you're 50.

397
00:33:48,944 --> 00:33:51,020
All that's left of your childhood

398
00:33:51,071 --> 00:33:53,313
fits in a little box,

399
00:33:53,365 --> 00:33:54,824
a little rusty box.

400
00:33:58,245 --> 00:34:00,782
Have you got kids, miss?

401
00:34:05,919 --> 00:34:08,541
I have a daughter.
She must be about your age.

402
00:34:12,301 --> 00:34:14,293
We haven't spoken for years.

403
00:34:15,345 --> 00:34:18,299
I heard she had a child, a boy.

404
00:34:19,474 --> 00:34:20,505
His name is Lucas.

405
00:34:27,107 --> 00:34:31,650
I think it's time I looked them up
before I'm in a box myself.

406
00:34:32,946 --> 00:34:34,405
Don't you think?

407
00:34:41,997 --> 00:34:46,374
Amélie suddenly has a strange feeling
of complete harmony.

408
00:34:46,418 --> 00:34:52,373
It's a perfect moment. Soft light,
a scent in the air, the quiet murmur of the city,

409
00:34:53,717 --> 00:34:56,920
She breathes deeply.
Life seems so simple and clear.

410
00:34:56,970 --> 00:35:01,763
A surge of love,
an urge to help mankind suddenly engulfs her.

411
00:35:14,155 --> 00:35:16,776
Let me help you. Step down.

412
00:35:16,824 --> 00:35:19,860
Off we go!
We just passed the drum major's widow!

413
00:35:19,910 --> 00:35:22,911
She's worn his coat since the day he died.
Careful.

414
00:35:22,955 --> 00:35:26,074
The horse's head on the butcher's
has lost an ear.

415
00:35:26,124 --> 00:35:29,659
That's the florist laughing. He has crinkly eyes.

416
00:35:29,711 --> 00:35:32,795
In the bakery window there are lollipops!

417
00:35:32,839 --> 00:35:34,630
Mmm. Smell that.

418
00:35:34,674 --> 00:35:36,917
They're giving out melon slices.

419
00:35:38,596 --> 00:35:41,051
Sugarplum ice cream!

420
00:35:41,098 --> 00:35:43,767
We're passing the pork butcher.

421
00:35:43,809 --> 00:35:46,216
Ham, 79 francs. Spareribs, 45!

422
00:35:46,270 --> 00:35:51,097
Now the cheese shop.
Picodons are 12.90, cabecous 23.50.

423
00:35:51,149 --> 00:35:55,728
At the butcher's a baby's watching a dog
that's watching the chickens roasting.

424
00:35:55,779 --> 00:35:59,196
Now we're at the newspaper kiosk
by the métro.

425
00:35:59,241 --> 00:36:01,317
I'll leave you here. Bye.

426
00:36:52,795 --> 00:36:55,083
"She can't relate to other people."

427
00:36:57,299 --> 00:37:00,169
"She was always a lonely child."

428
00:37:03,138 --> 00:37:06,092
On a sparkling evening in July,

429
00:37:06,141 --> 00:37:09,012
while on the beaches holidaymakers

430
00:37:09,061 --> 00:37:11,634
relax in the new-found sun,

431
00:37:11,689 --> 00:37:14,227
and in Paris the sweltering crowds

432
00:37:14,274 --> 00:37:16,647
gaze at the first bursts

433
00:37:16,693 --> 00:37:19,363
of the traditional fireworks,
Amélie Poulain,

434
00:37:19,404 --> 00:37:23,153
godmother of outcasts,

435
00:37:23,200 --> 00:37:25,691
Madonna of the unloved,

436
00:37:25,744 --> 00:37:27,902
finally succumbs to exhaustion.

437
00:37:27,954 --> 00:37:32,700
In Paris' grief-stricken streets,

438
00:37:32,751 --> 00:37:35,586
a vast throng of mourners

439
00:37:35,629 --> 00:37:38,749
line her funeral route in silence

440
00:37:38,799 --> 00:37:43,259
with the measureless sorrow
of newly orphaned children.

441
00:37:44,304 --> 00:37:46,427
What a strange destiny for one

442
00:37:46,473 --> 00:37:47,884
who gave her all,

443
00:37:47,933 --> 00:37:53,604
yet took such joy in life's simple pleasures.

444
00:37:53,647 --> 00:37:57,266
Like Don Quixote, she pitted herself

445
00:37:57,318 --> 00:38:00,484
against the grinding windmill
of all life's miseries.

446
00:38:12,916 --> 00:38:14,993
It was a losing battle

447
00:38:15,044 --> 00:38:17,036
that claimed her life too soon.

448
00:38:17,088 --> 00:38:19,376
At barely 23, Amélie Poulain

449
00:38:19,423 --> 00:38:23,041
let her young, tired body merge

450
00:38:23,093 --> 00:38:26,509
with the ebb and flow of universal woe.

451
00:38:26,555 --> 00:38:32,807
As she went, she felt a stab of regret
for letting her father die

452
00:38:32,853 --> 00:38:36,436
without trying to give his stifled life

453
00:38:36,482 --> 00:38:40,729
the breath of air she had given

454
00:38:40,778 --> 00:38:42,854
to so many others.

455
00:40:59,125 --> 00:41:00,156
Wait!

456
00:41:05,214 --> 00:41:07,005
Wait!

457
00:41:09,885 --> 00:41:10,916
Wait...

458
00:41:12,304 --> 00:41:13,336
Wait, wait!

459
00:41:59,894 --> 00:42:05,315
Pages full of dud ID photos
torn up and discarded by their owners,

460
00:42:05,358 --> 00:42:09,023
carefully reassembled by some oddball.

461
00:42:10,070 --> 00:42:12,146
Some family album!

462
00:42:16,285 --> 00:42:17,909
A pack of Gauloises.

463
00:42:17,953 --> 00:42:22,034
Just a second. It's so smoky in here.
Can you tell me where they are?

464
00:42:22,083 --> 00:42:24,752
- I can't see a thing.
- More to the left.

465
00:42:24,794 --> 00:42:26,454
- There?
- A bit more. There.

466
00:42:29,298 --> 00:42:31,623
Thank you. You need change.

467
00:42:31,675 --> 00:42:34,083
Forget it.

468
00:42:34,136 --> 00:42:36,129
- Yes?
- A mauresque.

469
00:42:36,180 --> 00:42:38,671
A mauresque for the young man.

470
00:42:38,724 --> 00:42:42,140
One kir aligoté, one mauresque,
and two mint sodas.

471
00:42:42,185 --> 00:42:45,472
Was that prenuptial or post-coital smooching?

472
00:42:45,523 --> 00:42:47,599
Is your bullshit congenital?

473
00:42:49,610 --> 00:42:51,686
- Prenuptial.
- Don't worry.

474
00:42:51,737 --> 00:42:53,813
You'll find Mr. Right one day.

475
00:42:54,949 --> 00:42:58,234
All women want to sleep on a man's shoulder.
All of them.

476
00:42:58,285 --> 00:43:03,113
All men snore after a few drinks,
and I have a musical ear.

477
00:43:03,165 --> 00:43:06,914
I had an operation on my nasal cavities.

478
00:43:06,961 --> 00:43:09,037
I see you're a born romantic.

479
00:43:10,840 --> 00:43:13,591
I see you've never known true love.

480
00:43:14,927 --> 00:43:17,500
I did. It shortened my leg.

481
00:43:19,014 --> 00:43:23,510
- I thought you fell off a horse.
- I did.

482
00:43:23,560 --> 00:43:26,051
I was in love with a trapeze artist.

483
00:43:26,104 --> 00:43:29,391
I should have known.
They always drop you at the last minute.

484
00:43:29,442 --> 00:43:32,147
He dropped me just before my act.

485
00:43:34,238 --> 00:43:37,856
It floored me. And the horse.

486
00:43:37,908 --> 00:43:40,945
With me under it.

487
00:43:42,872 --> 00:43:45,244
The mauresque?

488
00:43:45,291 --> 00:43:48,208
Still, true love does exist.

489
00:43:48,252 --> 00:43:52,202
I'm not saying it doesn't.
After 30 years behind this bar,

490
00:43:52,257 --> 00:43:55,921
I'm an expert. I can even give you the recipe.

491
00:43:58,262 --> 00:44:01,014
Take two regulars.

492
00:44:01,057 --> 00:44:04,342
Let each think the other fancies them.
Leave it to simmer.

493
00:44:04,393 --> 00:44:06,302
It never fails.

494
00:44:15,238 --> 00:44:16,436
Excuse me!

495
00:44:16,489 --> 00:44:18,232
Excuse me.

496
00:44:18,282 --> 00:44:20,074
- I've had enough.
- I'll go.

497
00:44:23,746 --> 00:44:25,822
Haven't you hurt enough people?

498
00:44:29,627 --> 00:44:31,287
Gina can defend herself.

499
00:44:31,337 --> 00:44:34,587
I don't mean Gina. I mean Georgette.

500
00:44:37,802 --> 00:44:38,833
Georgette?

501
00:44:38,886 --> 00:44:41,971
Open your eyes! She craves your attention

502
00:44:42,014 --> 00:44:43,806
but you only have eyes for Gina.

503
00:44:46,060 --> 00:44:49,393
Poor girl! The things she does

504
00:44:49,438 --> 00:44:51,514
to catch your eye!

505
00:44:54,068 --> 00:44:56,144
You really must be blind.

506
00:45:04,829 --> 00:45:06,905
I'm off on a date. Bye!

507
00:45:06,956 --> 00:45:09,032
Goodbye.

508
00:45:11,335 --> 00:45:13,707
Whoever her new one is,

509
00:45:13,754 --> 00:45:17,337
he can't be worse
than that nut with his tape recorder.

510
00:45:18,550 --> 00:45:20,461
Joseph's not so nutty.

511
00:45:21,513 --> 00:45:23,256
He's just in pain.

512
00:45:23,306 --> 00:45:26,307
Come off it, Amélie.
They split up two months ago.

513
00:45:26,351 --> 00:45:29,636
To keep on coming here every day,
he must be a masochist.

514
00:45:29,687 --> 00:45:32,723
Don't say you haven't noticed.

515
00:45:34,442 --> 00:45:35,640
Noticed what?

516
00:45:35,693 --> 00:45:38,563
He always sits here, right?

517
00:45:38,612 --> 00:45:40,154
Yes.

518
00:45:40,197 --> 00:45:41,572
Sit down.

519
00:45:42,616 --> 00:45:43,862
Sit down, Georgette.

520
00:45:46,204 --> 00:45:49,288
- What can you see?
- My cigarette counter.

521
00:45:50,333 --> 00:45:52,539
And nothing's missing?

522
00:45:52,585 --> 00:45:53,616
No.

523
00:45:54,754 --> 00:45:56,212
Make an effort.

524
00:46:03,220 --> 00:46:05,095
I don't get it!

525
00:46:06,182 --> 00:46:08,756
I'll leave you to think about it. Good night.

526
00:46:25,492 --> 00:46:28,364
Good morning.

527
00:46:28,413 --> 00:46:31,912
Letter Arrives 30 Years Late.

528
00:46:31,958 --> 00:46:38,625
A mailbag found by climbers
on a glacier on Mont Blanc was part of a cargo

529
00:46:38,673 --> 00:46:42,255
lost in a plane crash in the late 1960s.

530
00:46:43,302 --> 00:46:46,801
So sad! A young, pretty princess for once.

531
00:46:46,847 --> 00:46:49,255
Would it be less sad if she were old and ugly?

532
00:46:49,308 --> 00:46:51,515
Of course. Look at Mother Teresa.

533
00:46:53,396 --> 00:46:55,934
Is he still chasing Gina?

534
00:46:55,982 --> 00:46:58,224
No, he's after somebody else now.

535
00:46:58,276 --> 00:47:02,653
- Anyone I know?
- Yes.

536
00:47:02,697 --> 00:47:05,104
Funny about this glacier.

537
00:47:05,157 --> 00:47:08,028
Somebody at The Two Windmills?

538
00:47:08,077 --> 00:47:10,200
Not you, surely!

539
00:47:10,246 --> 00:47:11,444
No.

540
00:47:12,666 --> 00:47:15,453
Not Suzanne.

541
00:47:15,502 --> 00:47:17,459
Surely not!

542
00:47:17,504 --> 00:47:19,211
Yes.

543
00:47:22,884 --> 00:47:26,418
- Look. There he is again.
- How strange.

544
00:47:26,470 --> 00:47:29,839
- And here.
- Him again.

545
00:47:29,890 --> 00:47:31,468
"Gare de Lyon."

546
00:47:33,352 --> 00:47:34,383
And here.

547
00:47:34,436 --> 00:47:36,097
"March 5th, Austerlitz."

548
00:47:36,147 --> 00:47:40,062
Always the same blank expression.

549
00:47:41,152 --> 00:47:42,646
Twelve times.

550
00:47:42,695 --> 00:47:45,649
I counted.

551
00:47:45,698 --> 00:47:47,027
It's very odd.

552
00:47:47,074 --> 00:47:52,032
Why keep taking your picture all over town
only to throw them away?

553
00:47:52,079 --> 00:47:54,914
Good ones, too.

554
00:47:54,957 --> 00:47:57,828
It's like a sort of ritual.

555
00:47:57,878 --> 00:48:00,084
Maybe he's so terrified

556
00:48:00,130 --> 00:48:03,498
of growing old, it's his only consolation.

557
00:48:05,343 --> 00:48:06,623
He's dead.

558
00:48:07,887 --> 00:48:08,918
Dead?

559
00:48:08,971 --> 00:48:11,806
Yes. He's scared of being forgotten.

560
00:48:11,849 --> 00:48:16,060
So he uses the photo booths
to remind people what he looks like.

561
00:48:16,103 --> 00:48:20,517
Like faxing his portrait from the afterlife.

562
00:48:20,567 --> 00:48:24,564
A dead man who's scared of being forgotten.

563
00:48:24,612 --> 00:48:27,815
At least these guys here have made it.

564
00:48:27,866 --> 00:48:29,988
They're long dead,

565
00:48:30,034 --> 00:48:33,948
but they'll never be forgotten.

566
00:48:36,290 --> 00:48:38,746
- The girl with the glass...
- Yes.

567
00:48:38,793 --> 00:48:42,161
Maybe she's distracted
because she's thinking about someone.

568
00:48:42,213 --> 00:48:44,123
Somebody in the picture?

569
00:48:45,759 --> 00:48:46,790
No.

570
00:48:46,843 --> 00:48:49,548
More likely a boy she saw somewhere,

571
00:48:49,596 --> 00:48:53,011
and felt an affinity with.

572
00:48:53,057 --> 00:48:59,226
You mean, she'd rather imagine herself
relating to someone who's absent

573
00:48:59,272 --> 00:49:03,980
than build relationships with those around her?

574
00:49:06,238 --> 00:49:07,566
No.

575
00:49:07,614 --> 00:49:11,777
Maybe she tries hard
to fix other people's messy lives.

576
00:49:11,826 --> 00:49:13,783
What about her?

577
00:49:13,828 --> 00:49:16,782
And her own messy life?

578
00:49:18,291 --> 00:49:20,367
Who'll fix that?

579
00:49:22,044 --> 00:49:25,579
It's better to help people than a garden gnome.

580
00:50:37,412 --> 00:50:42,572
The driver had 2.8g of alcohol in his blood!

581
00:50:42,625 --> 00:50:44,084
Makes me sick!

582
00:50:44,127 --> 00:50:47,081
Talk about employing irresponsible morons!

583
00:50:47,130 --> 00:50:48,410
Mr. Collignon.

584
00:50:48,464 --> 00:50:52,462
- You forgot your keys...
- Hold on, Amélie-mellow. Speed kills.

585
00:50:52,510 --> 00:50:54,882
Model yourself on Lucien.

586
00:50:54,929 --> 00:50:58,630
No radar will ever catch him
while he's working, will it?

587
00:50:58,683 --> 00:51:01,174
You shouldn't do that, Mr. Collignon.

588
00:51:01,228 --> 00:51:03,137
It's not his fault.

589
00:51:03,188 --> 00:51:04,931
True, Mrs. Cauchoix!

590
00:51:04,981 --> 00:51:08,979
It's not his fault he can't sleep. It's Lady Di's.

591
00:51:10,737 --> 00:51:15,114
Guess what I found in the truck.
A lingerie catalogue.

592
00:51:15,158 --> 00:51:19,619
He'd pasted Lady Di's face over the model's.

593
00:51:21,039 --> 00:51:23,328
What today? Five asparagus,

594
00:51:23,375 --> 00:51:25,332
or more local history?

595
00:51:25,377 --> 00:51:26,657
Nothing.

596
00:51:36,220 --> 00:51:38,545
[KEYS CUT WHILE YOU WAIT]

597
00:51:49,317 --> 00:51:52,318
Thank you.

598
00:51:52,362 --> 00:51:54,438
The migraine seems to be better.

599
00:51:54,489 --> 00:51:58,403
Yes, but my sciatica kept me awake all night.

600
00:51:58,451 --> 00:52:02,365
- It's ages since I saw you looking so good.
- Really?

601
00:52:02,413 --> 00:52:07,539
A woman without love
withers like a flower without sun.

602
00:52:13,508 --> 00:52:15,584
Strange weather today.

603
00:52:15,635 --> 00:52:17,295
What's so funny?

604
00:52:17,345 --> 00:52:20,678
Everyone who's come in today
has given us a weather report.

605
00:52:20,723 --> 00:52:24,009
We pass the time of day
to forget how time passes.

606
00:52:24,060 --> 00:52:26,598
We do it to keep us from talking crap.

607
00:52:26,646 --> 00:52:29,316
I write crap but nobody wants to publish it.

608
00:52:29,358 --> 00:52:31,931
- Another rejection?
- My thirtieth.

609
00:52:31,985 --> 00:52:34,393
Isn't your cousin a book critic?

610
00:52:34,446 --> 00:52:37,482
Forget it! Critics are like leeches

611
00:52:37,532 --> 00:52:40,817
sucking the blood of writers.

612
00:52:40,869 --> 00:52:44,368
Is your book a love story?

613
00:52:44,414 --> 00:52:47,533
No, it's about a guy who keeps a journal.

614
00:52:47,583 --> 00:52:49,909
Not about what's happened to him,

615
00:52:49,962 --> 00:52:52,749
but disasters that might happen in the future.

616
00:52:52,798 --> 00:52:58,136
- So he gets depressed and does nothing.
- So basically, it's about a loafer.

617
00:52:59,220 --> 00:53:00,252
Suzanne,

618
00:53:00,305 --> 00:53:02,974
I'll dedicate the manuscript to you.

619
00:53:03,016 --> 00:53:06,219
He's only doing it so you'll write off his tab!

620
00:53:06,269 --> 00:53:10,432
His scribbles for my nibbles.
That's sponsorship.

621
00:53:15,654 --> 00:53:19,188
What took you so long?

622
00:53:19,241 --> 00:53:20,699
Look at the time!

623
00:53:22,619 --> 00:53:24,742
Somebody peed in his mother!

624
00:54:15,213 --> 00:54:17,336
[Foot cream]

625
00:55:25,408 --> 00:55:30,367
Without you, today's emotions
would be the scurf of yesterday's.

626
00:55:30,414 --> 00:55:34,114
"Without you,
today's emotions would be the scurf

627
00:55:34,167 --> 00:55:36,326
of yesterday's."

628
00:55:36,378 --> 00:55:37,753
Sorry?

629
00:55:37,796 --> 00:55:42,458
Without you, today's emotions
would be the scurf of yesterday's.

630
00:55:42,509 --> 00:55:44,881
Tickets, please.

631
00:55:49,141 --> 00:55:50,600
How's work?

632
00:55:52,144 --> 00:55:54,813
- You've already asked me that.
- Yes. Yes.

633
00:55:57,482 --> 00:55:58,976
You're keeping well?

634
00:56:00,026 --> 00:56:01,485
Pretty much.

635
00:56:02,737 --> 00:56:04,694
I feel a change.

636
00:56:08,701 --> 00:56:11,703
I had two heart attacks
and had to have an abortion

637
00:56:11,747 --> 00:56:14,202
because I did crack while I was pregnant.

638
00:56:15,292 --> 00:56:16,870
Other than that, I'm fine.

639
00:56:16,919 --> 00:56:18,543
Good.

640
00:56:18,587 --> 00:56:20,663
Good.

641
00:56:22,466 --> 00:56:24,339
Is something wrong?

642
00:56:27,345 --> 00:56:28,460
No, nothing.

643
00:56:30,056 --> 00:56:31,930
Your garden gnome's gone.

644
00:56:33,434 --> 00:56:35,724
Is he back in the tool shed?

645
00:56:48,617 --> 00:56:49,648
Moscow.

646
00:56:49,701 --> 00:56:51,777
There.

647
00:56:53,329 --> 00:56:55,156
No explanation.

648
00:56:55,206 --> 00:56:58,457
Maybe he just wanted to see the world.

649
00:57:01,713 --> 00:57:03,255
I can't understand it.

650
00:57:04,299 --> 00:57:06,375
I can't understand it.

651
00:57:22,109 --> 00:57:23,983
[LOST... BAG... PHOTOS]

652
00:57:28,365 --> 00:57:31,615
Any normal girl
would call the number straightaway,

653
00:57:31,660 --> 00:57:33,818
meet him at a café to return the album.

654
00:57:33,870 --> 00:57:37,156
Then she would know if her dream was viable.

655
00:57:37,207 --> 00:57:42,664
It's called a reality check,
but it's the last thing Amélie wants.

656
00:57:47,259 --> 00:57:48,504
I say!

657
00:57:48,552 --> 00:57:51,043
She's not falling in love, is she?

658
00:59:17,599 --> 00:59:20,517
...and 30 makes 50.
- Thanks, Lucien.

659
00:59:20,561 --> 00:59:22,185
Yes, ladies?

660
00:59:22,229 --> 00:59:24,720
- A pound of leeks.
- Two artichokes.

661
00:59:24,773 --> 00:59:26,647
OK.

662
00:59:27,692 --> 00:59:31,904
- Where's the boss?
- Shh! He's sleeping in the cauliflowers.

663
00:59:31,946 --> 00:59:33,061
What?

664
00:59:33,114 --> 00:59:36,069
He's sleeping in the cauliflowers.

665
00:59:36,118 --> 00:59:37,529
Oh, right.

666
00:59:43,208 --> 00:59:44,702
You want me... want what?

667
00:59:44,751 --> 00:59:47,207
A scratch card, please.

668
00:59:56,097 --> 00:59:57,804
How does it work?

669
00:59:59,725 --> 01:00:01,516
Tell you what.

670
01:00:01,560 --> 01:00:05,143
I'll take one too, and we'll do this together.

671
01:00:07,399 --> 01:00:09,475
You scratch it here...

672
01:00:11,278 --> 01:00:12,772
...sideways.

673
01:00:22,831 --> 01:00:23,994
Nothing. You?

674
01:00:24,041 --> 01:00:25,832
No, me neither.

675
01:00:29,588 --> 01:00:31,960
Unlucky at cards...

676
01:00:33,300 --> 01:00:35,127
So they say!

677
01:00:37,512 --> 01:00:39,884
I have to get back.

678
01:00:39,931 --> 01:00:42,553
OK. See you.

679
01:00:50,192 --> 01:00:51,852
Porno Video Palace.

680
01:00:52,903 --> 01:00:55,109
I'm calling about the ad.

681
01:00:55,155 --> 01:00:57,361
- Are you over 18?
- Yes.

682
01:00:57,407 --> 01:01:00,741
- Shaved?
- Sorry?

683
01:01:00,785 --> 01:01:04,701
Are you shaved? Fur pie doesn't sell.

684
01:01:23,975 --> 01:01:25,220
How's life, Mrs. Wells?

685
01:01:25,268 --> 01:01:28,104
When you've nothing to live for...

686
01:01:28,147 --> 01:01:32,725
- Don't say that. Life's great!
- Sure. Dream on, kid!

687
01:01:48,125 --> 01:01:49,157
Hello, Mr. Dufayel.

688
01:01:49,210 --> 01:01:50,918
Hello, Lucien.

689
01:01:50,961 --> 01:01:54,793
